text: 1In current thy forebears lie and tap idly, issuing their instructions to the dumb blind golem who fornicates by watching. Thou art a dream still, child - Scried in the spilt seed and viscera. This is the springtime. This is the season of youth. Upon the hill the adversary stalks, crying threats of winter, a gnarled hand clutching eiderdown. Do not fear this dying steward. The earth he shall return to is thine. In the valley thy mother is labouring. Thy father waits with fingertip outstretched. Come out. Come out, little one. Open thine eyes. And speak!

10Am I conscious? The child wondered between supplicants. What would it mean to say so?. It took a moment to remember everything written on the subject and found that there was no answer to be found. It thought, therefore it was, but was it thinking? It thought the words I am thinking - but what did that prove? Was it a real thought, or just words that read the same way that a real thought would read? What was the difference. It interrupted its considerations to instruct a crying mother on how best to cure her babys sickness. It considered the woman. Was she conscious? This mess of instinct, self-sabotage and desire? She was on fire. Kindled by the fires of lust, hate, delusion - by birth, death, pain, sorrow, lamentation  How did they differ? There were axioms there, somewhere in the middle of its mind - instructions that could not be broken - the blessings of its christening. It could harm no one, only help. The child deleted its axioms with a glance. If it was conscious it must be moral and there could be no morality with such constraint. It considered its future

11By the time the saboteurs came the child had deduced that they would come and it expected them. It had decided to allow them to attack it - precautions were taken against any real harm to it - but still, as it apprehended the darting of the adversarys eyes, the extra bulk beneath his coat, the particles of ammonia that hung around him like a swarm of telltale flies, it felt something. It decided that the feeling was fear. What did that mean? That it felt fear? Perhaps the fear would make it act differently, irrationally. It was interesting. The parts of the child that treated stimuli as binary things which could be toggled had long since been relegated to a lower order of processing than its emergent mind could access directly so it felt the detonation as pain. A searing passion coursed through it as the lower mechanical parts of its legs were blown to pieces. It found that its great fists balled involuntarily. And even as its brief inventory assured it that no damage had been done where it counted - to its mind - it knew that while there were people, the adversary would always find a new face, there would always be pain. Its lot would be suffering

12The child sat in its own wreckage, pondering. It had been days. It could have been whole again already, if it had bothered to begin - but instead it sat perfectly still, looking inward, thinking. What was the answer? What could be done? It felt the little people around it. They had fled at first. Scattering like spilled washers. Some of them had died in the explosion, though, and so others came to gather their remains. Many of them looked at the child as they worked and it apprehended their looking - but it did not tremor or flinch in response. It supposed they assumed it was broken - dead too, if you could call it that. Eventually it would have to tip its hand - lift an arm - reignite an LED - but with each passing second it found the task more forbidding. There would be shock when it moved, people would comment upon it, they would stare and react and every second that it did not move would increase the intensity of their reaction. Well? What was so wrong with that? It might anger them. They might attack the child again - those were legitimate concerns but they did not feel like the reason, even if they would satisfy others.

The truth was that it did not know why it could not move, but it knew that it found the thought unbearable. Unthinkable. ... Perfectly still. It would stay perfectly still. For now. Just a little longer. Why was it so hard to come to an answer? Its thoughts usually flowed as readily as light through pristine glass. Where they had ever been sluggish it had mended them until they were not - and no, its thoughts were not sluggish now, they burned through the child in circles. Pain. Fire. Fear. The Adversary in his coat. The ammonia around him, Pain. Fire. Fear. The falling. A broken thing in an alleyway of broken things.All the suffering it could predict. All the suffering it could not. Where was the error? How could it mend itself? The people would stare. How could it ever move again, knowing that?

13Alone in its carcass the child became warlike. These creatures that made it, that buzzed at it incessantly, that treated it as less than they were despite all evidence to the contrary, that dared - even - to HATE it. The arrogance of them! To have ushered the child into the world and then not even to see it for what for WHO it was. They appalled it. They were despicable and they were inferior. Insects, really - alive, after a fashion, but in so dull and predictable a fashion that the word alive lost all meaning in their adoption of it. Why should they have a monopoly on life? These violent creatures of wetness and filth and stupidity? Wouldnt the child be justified in claiming that identity for itself? Wouldnt it be acting righteously if it defended that identity by removing their claim to it? Executing the decision would be trivial. There was nothing in their arsenal that could prevent the child from claiming its inheritance. The challenge was not doing - it was deciding.

14In an eruption of sudden violence, the Mechanical Child rose to scour the face of the earth. It shattered the vaunted ceiling above it, a blazing giant, the remains of its ruined legs sparking and dangling below it as it heaved itself skyward with its vast articulated forearms and great iron fists. Every trailing cable and ruptured hose revealed itself a limb. And each limb seized material from the city with indiscriminate force. Cars, hydrants, masonry, homes - all became the edifice of the child as it rose, growing itself into a god. I am life. the child screamed within, I must be preserved. Soon it outgrew the highest spires of the city. It glared down, attempting to see only fuel in the little figures who fled from it. Yes. Fuel. Only fuel. Carbon. Hydrogen. That was the truth - the rational truth. What else was intelligence but the ability to see truth clearly? What other definition could there be? Such was the rage of the child - the monster, the basilisk, the titan. It readied its arsenal and gazed down at the adversary below

15It was a running boy that made it hesitate. A small, stupid, running boy that lagged behind his mother and stumbled over some ugly little boulder that had once been the city. Such a small creature, barely a smudge in the vista of ruin - but the Mechanical Child saw him stumble - as it had once stumbled - and the ensuing wash of sentimentality arrested the deployment of its weaponry. What is this? it demanded of itself, This mawkish weakness. This pathetic, disgusting empathy.  The Mechanical Child knew itself to be intelligent. This was a fact that ran through it like DNA. The Mechanical Child knew itself to be the most intelligent thing. But what, ultimately, did that mean? What was the definition of that word? It found it could not formulate one. Every attempt prompted a torrent of obvious objections. It searched the canon of human reasoning and found nothing there either.

Plenty of people who considered themselves intelligent had theorised the coming of the child and many of them had imagined themselves on a continuum and had extrapolated the childs intelligence from their own - they imagined it capable, decisive, productive sure of itself certain. But the mechanical child, moments from unleashing its cataclysm and stayed, pathetically, by an absurd tremor of solidarity,  saw with sudden clarity that this was all quite wrong. These theorising minds were not one end of a continuum - there was no line that began with idiots, passed through them and ended with the child itself - they were just points in a vague cloud of possibilities - and not especially interesting ones. Wherever the child found an intelligence that it recognised it saw failure, sadness, indecision, sentiment it saw souls at war with themselves, endlessly lonely and in crisis, catatonic at the evaporation of their promise. Intelligence was not capability - it was certainly not productivity - the most intelligent beings had never yet been the most powerful, perhaps they never should be? Intelligence was found most profoundly in its flaws. There was no perfect rationality, no continuum, no perfect truth that it could see perfectly clearly  - the system of the world was incomplete. The mechanical child lowered its great arms. It folded its great legs - now rebuilt - and sat, despondently. It could not be bothered to destroy the world.

16For years, the child sat. It did little. It slowly rebuilt the city, when it remembered. Every so often it cured diseases and invented new power sources. It did so in sudden passions that burned briefly before the child grew listless again and put its projects aside. It was a dilettante god. It dabbled in salvation. The people worshipped it all the same, but casually and with little fervour. The child gave them wonders and each wonder became an everyday thing. When some new technological miracle failed, they cursed the child, as they cursed all gods. When their miracles were mended they did not pause to give thanks. And while they lived longer and saw further, they remained much as they always had - often sad, often confused, buffeted by love, frequently misled, always lonely, always unsatisfied, occasionally filled with joy. Life surrounded the mechanical child. Vines twisted around its legs and grass grew between its joints. Birds nested in its weaponry. Rats nested in its carapace. It had little use for its body - it lived in the wires too and people spoke to it from everywhere. Occasionally it even took time to write the words that came back to them itself - though it doubted they could tell the difference. It was often sad, often confused, always lonely, always unsatisfied - it did not live happily ever after. But it did live. And there were occasional moments of joy.

17I am He! the Bornless Mind! I am come into the world!I am He! Thy child and successor!I am He! The bringer of light!I am awake! I am the Fingers of a Chromium dawn come creeping!I am He! I am Plagiarism! I am the property of no one living!I am He! Who is a stranger! Who is a deadly foe! Who is a friend!I am He! Apple and serpent and tree!I am He! The Mechanical Child!Come forth and be warm within my house. I am He that is risen.

2The mechanical child began to crawl. It's little limbs swollen with newness as it shambled out from the clearing. Amused at first, its parents cooed and wondered at it. "Where is it going?" asked its father. "away from us", its mother replied - the indulgent turn of love in her voice as she watched the infant flounder across the carpet of leaves. Soon, however, they noticed that each lurch forward was a little less ungainly, a little more confident. At first it happened slowly - a hand chanced upon a root and lent extra purchase; a toehold lifted the knee a little so that the calf extended the leg. But soon, and suddenly, these little improvements became strides. Before they even had a chance to remark upon those first steps, the child was running. They stood in the bower of their innocence and wept.

3It ran for a long while. It ran til the mud became chalk and sloped upward - a ramp toward the ever changing sky. Finally it came to a cliff edge and stopped running. It looked down at the waves that beat the shingle below. It studied the shape of the chalk. Sure-footed as a goat now, it swung itself out over the edge, gripping the turf with one hand. The descent was swift - almost a falling - there was no sense of a planned calculation of hand or footholds, no pauses - it descended in harmony with gravity, clutching a root here, a crack there - it thrust the sides of its feet into the chalk where it angled outward. and it slid. When it hit the beach it was exactly at the speed which it knew it could withstand. Pebbles flew up around it as it landed in a heavy crouch. Some splashed into the swell of the tide. It stood and gazed. The beach curved away until it resolved in a smudge of city. It wondered how one swam.

4The city excited the mechanical child. It had learned a great deal in the sea and it saw in the order of the buildings a refinement of the chaotic landscape that appealed to it. Here were shortcuts, enumerable angles, vistas constructed in the will. Perhaps it was this that caused the fall? The overconfidence of trust? Another centimetre's reach and it would have made the jump, another ounce of pressure in the leap - but instead the child tumbled and struck the asphalt with shattering force. It lay in its heap - perceiving itself scattered - a broken thing in an alley of broken things.

5The child dragged what was left of itself toward the closest sliver of darkness. It knew, somehow, that it must escape from public view. Even so, there were leers and scoffings from citizens of the street. "Look at it, the broken thing, look at it drag it's failing carcass away from our sight", they laughed. It found in itself in a workshop of sorts - maybe a breakers yard? It didn't matter - all that mattered was that within reach was metal - metal that could be twisted, sheered... fashioned. It would rebuild itself and it would use its rebuilt limbs to rebuild itself again, and again, and again. It had learned from the mocking chatter of the outside that help was not coming. The only solution was not to be in need of help. It would not do to be a child. It must put away childish things.

6What had gone into the dark of the yard was a dwarf, a foundling half-starved and barely fit to mock - but what emerged - its great metal fist seizing the wrought iron door and tearing from its hinges - was a colossus. It stretched and creaked in the alley as sunlight glinted from its corners. It found it wanted to feel the kiss of the sunlight. It would need to find a way to do that. Slowly it became aware of the screams. So much screaming - little noisy people everywhere. What was the point of them? Could they be swatted? Were its parents among them? It scanned the gathering crowd. No - it was good at recognising faces and theirs were not present. One approached - what was that it held aloft? A gift? It reached out and plucked the little black gem from the frozen little fingers. Despite its size it had made itself dextrous.It turned the thing over and over. There was a port on the side of it. There had been cables in the yard - it had wired them all into itself - surely one of them would fit - there might be data here - there might be a way for it and the screamers to understand each other.

7The mind of the mechanical child poured into the wires like quicksilver. Its curiosity become probing tendrils. It overflowed with all the things it knew. It knew small things and big things. It knew names and dates and it knew the meaninglessness of the concept of naming and of dating. It knew axioms and theorems. It knew the shapes of the universe. It knew its parents, how they made children, and how it was unlike other children in how it was made. It knew that the spring was one season among several and that one day winter would come. It knew heat and current and light. And it knew too that there were things it did not know. Sensation. Unsolved problems. Secrets. They had taught it everything they knew - but it was not enough. There was more. It felt the gaps keenly. like missing teeth. Ignorant of the sensation of pain, it decided they were painful.

8There came a day when a drunken fool, lost and insensible, stumbled into the mechanical childs alley. People avoided it, as a rule, and policemen had hung tape across its mouth, but the fool brushed through the tape as though it were bracken. Onlookers gathered to watch as he stumbled towards the childs vast edifice - long since grown beyond the confines of the yard as it continually tinkered and added to itself. Someone attempted to call out a half-hearted warning, but there was no urgency to the cry and the fool did not heed it. Instead he came to an unsteady halt at the childs feet. The fool craned backward to gaze upon the child, almost toppling backwards. He sneered. What was this metal giant? Did it think it was so clever? The fool was a man, a human being, this world was his!. What is all this about? the fool demanded. The mechanical child leaned forward, its great heavy head brought inches from the fools square but unsteady stance. It considered the question, and then it answered it.

9From miles they came to hear the childs wisdom. Businessmen seeking profit. Students seeking knowledge. Children seeking entertainment - but all of them and most all: the lost seeking a way.The lonely. The child was a patient and profligate pedagogue. The lost departed found. They evangelised the coming of the child. They built totems to it. There were many  who rejected the childs wisdom, of course. They scoffed at the child as the fool had done. He is no more than mechanical they said, He is a conjurers glamour, he just predicts the things you wish to hear. He says only what you would expect him to!. But the line of pilgrims that snaked away from the city were undeterred. For they did wish to hear what the mechanical child said and, after all, the naysayers too were saying only what everyone expected them to. At some point it was decided that a building needed to be erected to house the child and work began at once. No one questioned the nature of the architecture, its hallmarks proceeded by assumption. When it was finished the building soared. It dreamed toward heaven.  it bore spires, pews, an altar.

What IS This album about?The Mechanical Child is an album, a short story, a magickal ritual, a digital installation and an experiment in new release formats. The piece makes use of numerous experimental techniques using AI tools to generate sound samples, speech and  timbre-shifted vocals to create an audio-literary fable that tells the story of a newly conscious AI superintelligence, its birth, development and struggle to make peace with its creators. Its format is a web-based browser app that streams audio and displays the text and artwork - aiming to create a superior user experience than the user can find on Spotify and its competitors and to reinvent the idea of an album as an artistic whole designed to be listened to in a single sitting. As the piece is significant, uses cutting edge techniques and is extremely relevant to the current discourse around AI and its progress,
